&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ***Clockwork Toy.*** This toy is a clockwork animal, monster, or person, such as a frog, mouse, bird, dragon, or soldier. When placed on the ground, the toy moves 5 feet across the ground on each of your turns in a random direction. It makes noises as appropriate to the creature it represents.

***Clothes, Cold Weather.*** Made of heavy cloth and fur, these clothes allow you to automatically succeed on saving throws against the effects of extreme cold. They provide no benefit if they are no longer dry.

\pagebreakNum

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ***Clothes, Hot Weather.*** Made of thin, breezy cloth, these clothes allow you to automatically succeed on saving throws against the effects of extreme heat.

***Compass.*** A simple device that always points north, unless disrupted by nearby magnetic fields. All Wisdom (Survival) checks made to determine location and direction while using a compass are made with advantage.

***Dynamite.*** As an action, a creature can light a stick of dynamite and throw it at a point up to 60 feet away. Each creature within 5 feet of that point must make a DC 13 Dexterity saving throw, taking 3d6 bludgeoning damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one.

A character can bind up to eight sticks together over 1 minute so they explode at the same time. Each additional stick increases the damage by 1d6 (to a maximum of 10d6) and the burst radius by 5 feet (to a maximum of 20 feet). A set of bound dynamite cannot be thrown more than 10 feet, but deals double damage to objects and structures.

Dynamite can be rigged with a longer fuse to explode after a set amount of time, usually 1 to 6 rounds. Roll initiative for the dynamite. After the set number of rounds goes by, the dynamite explodes on that initiative.

***Firework, Signal.*** A simple rocket that propels itself for 150 feet then explodes in a burst of colored sparks. When fired into the air, the explosion can be seen for up to 15 miles. 

***Lighter.*** This small container is capable of producing a tiny flame that sheds bright light in 5-foot radius and dim light for an additional 5 feet. Using it to light a torch—or anything else with exposed fuel—takes a ***BONUS*** action.

***Flashlight.*** This tube-shaped device, sometimes called an "electric torch," can be turned on or off as an action. It casts bright light in 60-foot cone and dim light for an additional 60 feet. A flashlight is powered by turning a crank on the side. Turning the crank for 10 minutes provides enough power for 8 hours.

***Glowstick.*** As an action, you can light one or more glowsticks, providing bright light in a 5-foot radius and dim light for an additional 5 feet. A lit glowstick starts to fade after 8 hours, no longer illuminating its surroundings (though it still sheds enough light to be noticed in the dark for another 4 hours). Once lit, a glowstick cannot be extinguished.

***Goggles.*** A set of goggles protects your eyes from wind, smoke, and other irritants. Goggles sometimes have special lenses, such as smoky glass to protect from bright lights and sparks or magnifying lenses for precision work.

***Grenade, Fragmentation.*** As an action, you can throw the grenade up to 60 feet away. Each creature within 5 feet of that point must succeed on a DC 12 Dexterity saving throw or take 3d6 piercing damage.

***Grenade, Incendiary.*** As an action, you can throw the grenade up to 60 feet away. Each creature within 5 feet of that point must succeed on a DC 12 Dexterity saving throw or take 1d6 fire damage and be set on fire. A creature on fire take 1d6 fire damage at the end of each of their turns unless they take an action make a DC 10 Dexterity check to extinguish the flame.

***Grenade, Smoke.*** As an action, you can throw the grenade up to 60 feet away. One round after a smoke grenade lands, it emits a cloud of smoke that creates a heavily obscured area in a 20-foot radius. A moderate wind (at least 10 miles per hour) disperses the smoke in 4 rounds; a strong wind (20 or more miles per hour) disperses it in 1 round.

***Lantern, Electric.*** An electric lantern has three settings, which you can switch between as an action: high, low, and off. When on the high setting, it sheds bright light in a 30-foot radius and dim light for an additional 30 feet. On the low setting, it sheds dim light for 5 feet. An electric lantern is powered by turning a crank on the side. Turning the crank for 10 minutes provides enough power for 8 hours on the high setting, or 48 hours on the low setting.

***Libram.*** This book of prayers, philosophy, and holy teachings can be used as a holy symbol.

***Music Box.*** When opened. this music box plays a single song at a moderate volume. The box stops playing when it reaches the song's end or when it is closed.

***Parachute.*** When wearing this backpack-shaped piece of gear, you can deploy it as a reaction while falling. If deployed while at least 120 feet above the ground, your falling speed is reduced to 60 feet per round until you land, taking no damage. While falling, your size becomes one size larger for purposes of space. Once it has been used, the parachute takes 10 minutes to repack.

***Rush'kah.*** This carved and painted wooden mask the size of a small shield is typically used by troll cultures as holy symbols for their spirit worship.

***Scope.*** A scope can be attached to a two-handed firearm or crossbow using 1 minute. You can use your bonus action to aim through the scope, gaining disadvantage on attack rolls against targets in normal range but removing the disadvantage of attacking at long range until the beginning of your next turn.

***Snap-o-matic.*** This device can be used to capture the image of whatever it is looking at and print it out on a small piece of special paper called film. When used, a small flashlight on the front of the device flashes brightly. Spare cartidges of film, each containing enough for ten snap-shots, can be bought for 1 gp each.

***Spyglass.*** When looking at distant objects through the twin tubes of this device, they appear to be twice as close. Spyglasses have an adjustable range, but are usually only effective when looking at objects more than 1/2 mile away.

***Timepiece.*** This pocket-sized device keeps perfect time. Wealthy gnomes and goblins are known to have elaborately decorated versions kept on a thin chain about their waist.

## New Tools
The following items can be selected as tool proficiencies in addition to the options presented in Chapter 5 of the Player's Handbook.

***Engineer's tools.*** This set of artisan's tools allows you to craft and maintain a wide variety of marvels, from firearms and explosives to gadgets and constructs. <!-- ***Gunsmith's tools.*** These artisan's tools are used not only to craft firearms and their ammunition, but explosives such as dynamite and grenades. --> 

***Enchanter's supplies.*** These artisan's tools are used to inspect and manipulate magic items and spells.

***Hearthstone card set.*** This game pits two opponents against each other using decks of thirty constructed by each player pulled from thousands of potential cards. Each card set comes with a protective box that includes dice, the rule book, and a catalog of official cards.

***Pandaren jihui board.*** This board game is designed to allow for both players to arrive at a satisfying conclusion and thus is a good way to pass the time peacefully.

\pagebreakNum

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ***Suturing kit.*** This set of needles, thread, and other tools is used to stitch together flesh. The usage of this kit varies from stapling together large wounds to creating taxidermy. Corporeal undead such as the forsaken have made use of these kits to repair and replace their rotting flesh and limbs. Proficiency with this kit allows you to add your proficiency bonus to any ability checks you make to stitch flesh or even simpler materials such as cloth or leather.

### Expanded Tool Descriptions
Below are expanded descriptions of potential uses of the new tools, following the rules set forth in Chapter 2 of Xanathar's Guide to Everything.

#### Enchanter's Supplies
These supplies are used to inspect and manipulate magic items and spells.

***Components.*** A set of enchanter's supplies includes several pouches of magic-infused powders and crystal shards, as well as small brushes, tweezers, a runed metal rod, and a pair of crystal lenses.

***Arcana.*** Proficiency with enchanter's supplies allows you to unlock more information on Arcana checks involving magic items.

***Investigation.*** When you inspect or research a magic item, your proficiency with enchanter's supplies grants additional insight.

***Detect Magic.*** By closely inspecting an item for 10 minutes, your proficiency with enchanter's supplies allows you to duplicate the effects of the *identify* spell. By using your enchanter's supplies and spending 1 minute walking around an area with no more than a 30 foot radius, you can instantaneously identify any magical auras, as the *detect magic* spell.

##### Enchanter's Supplies
Activity                                | DC
----------------------------------------|-----
Determine whether an item is magical    | 10
Disable a magical trap                  | Varies

#### Engineer's Tools
A set of engineer's tools allows you to craft and maintain a wide variety of marvels, from firearms and explosives to gadgets and constructs.

***Components.*** Engineer's tools come in a metal box with compartments containing a plethora of springs, gears, wires, powders, and other parts, as well as a variety of hammers, screwdrivers, and wrenches.

***Arcana, History.*** Your expertise lends you additional insight into firearms, explosives, and mechanical constructs or devices.

***Investigation, Perception.*** You can spot clues and make deductions that others might overlook when firearms, explosives, or mechanical constructs or devices are involved in an investigation.

***Repair.*** As part of a short rest, you can repair a single damaged firearm. With sufficient spare parts, you can restore 10 hit points to a mechanical construct or device for each hour of work.

***Mechanical Crafting.*** You can use this tool proficiency to create mechanical items. A character can spend money to collect raw materials, which weigh 1 pound for every 50 gp spent. The GM can allow a character to make a check using the indicated skill with advantage. As part of a long rest, you can use engineer's tools to make twenty firearm bullets or one stick of dynamite, electric lantern, flashlight, grenade, music box, scope, or spyglass. Subtract half the value of the created item from the total gp worth of raw materials you are carrying.

##### Engineer's Tools
Activity                                | DC
----------------------------------------|-----
Craft bullets using an unusual material | 15
Disarm an explosive                     | Varies


